WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.920
Thank you for taking the time. I want this to feel like a working session, not a one-way presentation.

2
00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:10.720
So I'm going to walk you through how I think about building LLM systems and organization can

3
00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:16.400
actually depend on. I'll cover the four areas you asked about, production rag architecture,

4
00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:22.880
a real case study with hard numbers, my evaluation approach, and the tooling ecosystem I lean on.

5
00:00:22.880 --> 00:00:28.160
I've left plenty of room for questions, so please stop me whenever something connects to a problem

6
00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:34.320
you're working through. I'm Munshul Sharma, 13 years in production systems, Masters in software

7
00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:40.480
engineering, author of rag in production, an inventor of the ILEI architecture for LLM's,

8
00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:46.960
patent pending with the USBTO. Take away a trajectory, not a job list. Each phase built the lens I

9
00:00:46.960 --> 00:00:53.280
bring to AI now. Distributed systems taught me to think about failure modes before the happy path.

10
00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:58.800
Agentic systems taught me to contain non-determinism with contracts and fallbacks.

11
00:00:58.800 --> 00:01:05.360
That framing transfers directly to language models. I don't see a model. I see a distributed system

12
00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:11.760
with a probabilistic component in the critical path, and that changes every architectural decision.

13
00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:16.960
My operating principle, treat the language model as the least reliable component,

14
00:01:16.960 --> 00:01:22.480
and architect everything around containing and measuring that uncertainty. In an environment

15
00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:28.720
where a confidently wrong answer has real cost, you need deterministic structure around a probabilistic

16
00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:35.280
core. If you ask most people what a rag implementation looks like, this is it. Chunk your documents,

17
00:01:35.280 --> 00:01:41.360
embed them, drop them in a vector database, retrieve top-k, hand the context to the model,

18
00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:47.360
get an answer. And honestly, this is a reasonable way to prove a concept in an afternoon.

19
00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:53.280
I've built this pipeline many times. It demos beautifully. The problem isn't that it's wrong.

20
00:01:53.280 --> 00:01:59.760
It's what it quietly assumes. Clean documents, no access sensitive content, no need for exact

21
00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:05.520
term matching, and that you'll know when the model gets something wrong. The moment it meets real data,

22
00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:12.400
real users, and real consequences, it breaks in specific, predictable ways. Fixed chunking

23
00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:18.400
splits documents at arbitrary boundaries. Tables get split midrow. Code blocks get split

24
00:02:18.400 --> 00:02:24.640
mid-function. Conclusions get cut from the caveats that make them accurate. Pure vector search fails

25
00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:31.520
silently on exact terms. Part numbers, regulatory identifiers, domain-specific acronyms.

26
00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:38.320
Semantic similarity gets you to the neighborhood and misses the specific document. No access control

27
00:02:38.320 --> 00:02:43.440
means the system's surfaces chunks the requesting user was never authorized to see.

28
00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:48.640
In a national lab environment, that's not a compliance footnote. It's a mission critical

29
00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:55.760
failure baked into the architecture. And without an evaluation harness, hallucinations ship silently.

30
00:02:55.760 --> 00:03:01.600
The model generates fluent, confident pros. You have no automated signal on whether any of

31
00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:07.920
it is grounded in what you retrieved. You find out when a user catches it, or worse, when they don't.

32
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.640
Every one of these is a production requirement the demo quietly ignored.

33
00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:18.800
The most important architectural decision I make. I split it into three distinct planes and treat

34
00:03:18.800 --> 00:03:24.960
each one as a first-class engineering concern. The knowledge plane is offline, governed,

35
00:03:24.960 --> 00:03:30.800
versioned, and reproducible. It runs as a batch process, not on the request path.

36
00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:38.720
Every chunk that exits this plane carries metadata, source, section, version, access control identity,

37
00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:45.600
PI classification tags, and full lineage. That metadata isn't decoration. It's how every

38
00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:51.600
downstream decision gets made correctly. The serving plane is online and latency sensitive.

39
00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:58.800
A query comes in, gets classified by input guardrails, expands to an embedding, hits hybrid retrieval

40
00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:05.360
with ACL filtering already applied, gets re-ranked, assembled into a context window,

41
00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:10.720
passed to the model, then validated by output guardrails before anything goes out.

42
00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:17.280
Every stage has a latency budget and a defined failure behavior. The control plane spans both.

43
00:04:17.280 --> 00:04:22.720
It's the evaluation harness that gates deployment, end-to-end distributed tracing,

44
00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:27.920
access governance with full audit logs, semantic caching, and cost controls.

45
00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:33.440
Here's why this separation matters. The knowledge plane and the serving plane fail differently,

46
00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:38.720
scale differently, and are owned by different people. The knowledge plane is about correctness

47
00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:45.440
over time. It can be slow, it can be batch, it just needs to be right. The serving plane is about

48
00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:52.400
latency and safety. Every request needs to be fast and auditable. Conflating them is the root

49
00:04:52.400 --> 00:04:58.240
cause of most production rag failures I've seen. Notice governance isn't a step at the end.

50
00:04:58.240 --> 00:05:05.440
Access control identity, PI tags, and lineage travel with every chunk from the moment of ingestion.

51
00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:11.600
ACLs are enforced at retrieval time, not display time. By the time a chunk reaches the model,

52
00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:17.040
the authorization decision has already been made. Now go back to those red failures.

53
00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:23.840
Fixed chunking, pure vector search, no access control, no evaluation, no guardrails.

54
00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:30.720
Every single one is now a named, testable, independently owned capability in this architecture.

55
00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:35.920
That's the difference between a demo and a system the lab can defend. The biggest lever

56
00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:41.120
on quality is not which model you choose. It's whether the right context gets in front of the

57
00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:47.120
model in the first place. The model can only be as good as what you handed. Hybrid retrieval,

58
00:05:47.120 --> 00:05:54.560
dense vectors combined with sparse BM25 is non-negotiable in technical and scientific domains.

59
00:05:54.560 --> 00:06:01.040
Pure semantic search is powerful but fails silently on exact terms. A specific part number,

60
00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:06.480
a regulatory standard identifier, a precise acronym, dense embeddings get the general

61
00:06:06.560 --> 00:06:14.080
neighborhood and miss the specific document. BM25 catches exact tokens. You need both signals

62
00:06:14.080 --> 00:06:19.280
and a fusion layer that knows how to combine them. Reranking is the second major lever.

63
00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:25.520
You pull a candidate set, maybe 50 documents, then run a cross encoder to Rescore relevance

64
00:06:25.520 --> 00:06:31.840
against the actual query. Cross encoders are slower, but that joint comparison of query against

65
00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:36.640
candidate produces dramatically better ordering. I've repeatedly seen re-ranking

66
00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:42.480
produce larger quality improvements than switching to a more capable and more expensive model.

67
00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:47.200
It's one of the highest return on investment changes you can make to a deployed system.

68
00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:52.800
Structure-aware chunking is the third. Tables, code blocks, and conclusions with their

69
00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:58.640
supporting caveats need to stay whole. If a results table gets split across two chunks,

70
00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:03.600
neither is useful in isolation. I use document type specific chunkers,

71
00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:08.560
and for heterogeneous sources, custom parsers rather than a generic text splitter.

72
00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:14.480
On evaluation, I measure retrieval and generation completely separately because they fail for

73
00:07:14.480 --> 00:07:20.480
completely different reasons. For retrieval, I track context precision and recall.

74
00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:24.880
Did we retrieve the right evidence? Did we miss anything critical?

75
00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:30.160
For generation, I track faithfulness. Is every claim grounded in what we retrieved

76
00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:36.320
and answer relevance? The eval said is built with domain experts, not auto-generated.

77
00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:41.680
It runs on every code change. Deployments are gated on it like a test suite.

78
00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:47.440
If we can't measure it, we don't ship it. A fluent, confident, unsupported answer is the

79
00:07:47.440 --> 00:07:52.480
most dangerous output a RAG system can produce. I'd rather the systems say,

80
00:07:52.480 --> 00:07:57.440
I don't have enough information than hallucinate. In a high-stakes environment,

81
00:07:57.440 --> 00:08:03.440
that refusal is a feature. Overconfidence is the failure mode that destroys long-term trust.

82
00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.080
My most recent enterprise project was a knowledge assistant that unified

83
00:08:08.080 --> 00:08:14.000
three systems engineers were losing hours across every day. A confluence Docs wiki,

84
00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.800
public Slack channels, and JIRA, one interface to query everything.

85
00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:24.240
The engineering was not simple. The hardest part wasn't the LLM. It was that each source

86
00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:30.320
breaks differently and required a completely separate ingestion strategy. The wiki goes stale.

87
00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:36.240
Documents from three years ago sit alongside documents from last week with no signal about

88
00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:43.120
which is canonical. I addressed this with recency decay waiting and canonical URL deduplication,

89
00:08:43.120 --> 00:08:49.280
so the most recently updated version always wins. Slack is conversational with no inherent

90
00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:56.000
ground truth. A thread might span 40 messages with the answer buried in message 32. I rebuilt

91
00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:01.600
threads as coherent units, extracted question and answer pairs were detectable, and applied a

92
00:09:01.600 --> 00:09:08.320
hard filter. Public channels only, enforced at ingestion time, not at query time. The access

93
00:09:08.320 --> 00:09:14.640
control decision for slack had to be made during ingest. It was the only safe and variant. JIRA

94
00:09:14.640 --> 00:09:20.240
is half structured fields and half freeform comment chains. The resolution comment often

95
00:09:20.240 --> 00:09:26.320
contains the actual answer. The ticket title is the category. I built field-aware parsers that

96
00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:32.080
weight resolve tickets higher and maintain link graph relationships between related issues.

97
00:09:32.160 --> 00:09:38.560
All three normalize into one unified access controlled versioned index. Here's the whole

98
00:09:38.560 --> 00:09:45.360
system into end. Three ingestion lanes, each with its own parsing logic converging into a

99
00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:51.600
single version knowledge plane. Every chunk carries its access control identity from the moment it's

100
00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:57.920
written. The serving plane starts with identity resolution. Every request maps to an authenticated

101
00:09:57.920 --> 00:10:05.200
user via OIDC, then to group memberships, then to what's retrievable. That ACL filter runs at

102
00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:12.160
the vector store query level. Unauthorized chunks are never retrieved, never ranked, never assembled.

103
00:10:12.160 --> 00:10:17.920
The data never reaches the model in the first place. Input guardrails scope the query,

104
00:10:17.920 --> 00:10:26.720
check for injection patterns, flag PI. Hybrid retrieval runs BM25 plus dense KNN, ACL filtered.

105
00:10:26.720 --> 00:10:33.280
The cross encoder re-ranker scores the top candidates. The LLM generates a grounded response.

106
00:10:33.280 --> 00:10:39.440
An LLM as judge scores groundedness before the answer leaves the system. Low faithfulness means

107
00:10:39.440 --> 00:10:46.160
refuse or regenerate, not pass through. The control plane gates everything. The evaluation

108
00:10:46.160 --> 00:10:52.560
harness as a deployment gate, open telemetry tracing on every span, governance logs, and

109
00:10:52.560 --> 00:10:58.640
thumbs up, thumbs down feedback feeding continuously back into the eval set. Nothing ships without

110
00:10:58.640 --> 00:11:04.640
passing the eval gate. Here's what it delivered in production. Median time to answer dropped by 80%.

111
00:11:05.600 --> 00:11:11.520
Engineers who used to spend 15 minutes hunting across three systems were getting answers in under

112
00:11:11.520 --> 00:11:18.800
90 seconds. Across the org that compounded to over 30,000 hours saved year over year. Faithfulness on

113
00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:26.800
our evaluation set held above 0.92. Engineers went from three interfaces to one. What I learned,

114
00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:32.960
per source ingestion strategy matters more than the LLM choice. The model was almost a commodity

115
00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:39.040
decision. The engineering value was in the ingestion design, the chunking, the retrieval,

116
00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:44.480
and the evaluation harness. Every meaningful quality improvement came from retrieval and

117
00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:51.040
chunking changes, not model upgrades. Hybrid retrieval plus re-ranking beat a model upgrade

118
00:11:51.040 --> 00:11:56.960
every time we ran the comparison. An eval harness built with subject matter experts was the only

119
00:11:56.960 --> 00:12:02.640
way we could ship with confidence. The domain experts caught failure modes our engineering team

120
00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:08.160
never would have thought to write test cases for. The trade off I made consciously and would make

121
00:12:08.160 --> 00:12:14.720
again precision over coverage. Refuse over guess when retrieval confidence is low. More,

122
00:12:14.720 --> 00:12:20.720
I don't have enough information responses in the early rollout. One confident wrong answer in the

123
00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:27.680
first two weeks destroys trust that takes months to rebuild. High recall is a long term goal. High

124
00:12:27.680 --> 00:12:33.120
precision from day one is how you earn the right to expand scope. The part I'm proudest of isn't

125
00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:39.200
the architecture. It's that I got security, data owners, legal, and subject matter experts

126
00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:45.200
aligned on access policy before we wrote a line of production code. The evaluation gate moved the

127
00:12:45.200 --> 00:12:52.240
team from it looks good to me to measured, auditable, and defensible. I'm opinionated about tooling,

128
00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:59.120
but loyal to capabilities, not vendors. On orchestration, Langchain and LAMA index are excellent for

129
00:12:59.200 --> 00:13:05.520
prototyping. You get to a working demo in hours. In production, I keep a thin custom layer on the

130
00:13:05.520 --> 00:13:12.560
critical path, retrieval, assembly, guardrails, so I can instrument it, test it, and swap components

131
00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:18.320
without untangling of frameworks abstractions. The framework is a scaffold, not a permanent

132
00:13:18.320 --> 00:13:24.960
dependency. On models, I evaluate on capability per dollar, latency, and whether the model can

133
00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:30.960
operate inside the security boundary. In a national lab environment, that last criterion

134
00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:36.720
often dominates every other. Open weight models like LAMA and Mistral earn their place not

135
00:13:36.720 --> 00:13:42.000
primarily because they're cheaper, they're often not, once you factor in infrastructure,

136
00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:48.800
but because they can run inside the air gap. Frontier models like CLOD and GPT for a best-in-class

137
00:13:48.800 --> 00:13:54.240
for complex reasoning, but they require data to leave the security perimeter. You need a clear

138
00:13:54.240 --> 00:14:00.000
policy on which workload classifications can use which model tier. On vector stores,

139
00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:05.440
put vector for teams already on Postgres who want minimal operational overhead,

140
00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:12.160
Milvis or Kdrant at scale with complex filtering, Azure AI search for native hybrid retrieval

141
00:14:12.160 --> 00:14:18.640
in enterprise Azure environments. The decision is almost never about raw performance. It's about

142
00:14:18.640 --> 00:14:24.560
ACL metadata filtering support and what your infrastructure team can operate it to in the morning.

143
00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:29.760
On evaluation, ROGA style metrics for retrieval and generation separately,

144
00:14:29.760 --> 00:14:36.480
custom harnesses for domain-specific cases, LLM as judge calibrated against human expert labels.

145
00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:41.840
The tooling matters less than the process. The eval set must be built with people who know

146
00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:48.240
what correct looks like. On observability, I won't ship an LLM system without self-hosted

147
00:14:48.240 --> 00:14:55.120
length use wired to open telemetry. Every retrieval, every model call, every guardrail decision

148
00:14:55.120 --> 00:15:00.880
needs to be traceable end-to-end. Cost attribution and latency profiling need to be

149
00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:06.400
on by default. In a deterministic outcomes environment, I won't hand reliability to a

150
00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:13.680
system I can't trace, test or explain. Let me pull this together. The goal of any LLM system

151
00:15:13.680 --> 00:15:19.600
in a mission critical environment shouldn't be can we build a working demo. It should be,

152
00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:25.920
can we build something the organization can defend, audit and trust at scale? Can we measure it?

153
00:15:25.920 --> 00:15:29.760
Can we explain why it's right? Can we improve it without guessing?

154
00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:34.960
Every decision I've walked you through, the three-plane architecture, hybrid retrieval with

155
00:15:34.960 --> 00:15:40.960
re-ranking, evaluation as a deployment gate, ACL enforcement at retrieval time.

156
00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:43.600
Those aren't complexity for its own sake.
